63. faba Pythagorae cognata. For the allusion cp. Epp. 1. 12. 21 n., and Juv. S. 15. 173. ‘ Pythagoras cunctis ani- malibus abstinuit qui Tanquam homine, et ventri indulsit non omne legumen‚’ with Mayor’s exhaustive note. The reference is to the Pythagorean proverb κυάμων ἀπέχεσθαι Diog. Laeit. 8. 18. It is one osa series of short rules on diet, some of which were generally in- terpreted literally, some as metaphors. Cicero mentions it (de Div. 1. 30. 62) ‘Pythagoricis interdictum ne faba vesce- rentur,’ and explains it ‘ quod habet inflationem magnam is cibus, tranquilli- tati mentis quaerentis vera contrariam.' Many other fanciful reasons are given. The ground given in the text> connecting it with the doctrine of metempsychosis, as though in eating a bean you might be unconsciously eating a kinsman, whether it be an original jest of Horace’s or not, suits well with the tone ofamused interest with which he habitually refers to the Pythagorean school. See introd. to Od. 1. 28, and cp. also his treatment of an— other Pythagorean proverb in Sat. 2. 3.
